1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:06,899
You're listening to: Putting an ML Model in Production: A Backend Engineer's Guide to Inference APIs.

2
00:00:06,899 --> 00:00:10,769
Serving a model is a backend problem, not a data-science one.

3
00:00:10,769 --> 00:00:23,593
A practical guide to production inference APIs — latency vs throughput, batching, GPU concurrency, caching, autoscaling cold starts, and the failure modes that don't exist in a notebook.

4
00:00:23,593 --> 00:00:24,651
Let's get started.

5
00:00:24,651 --> 00:00:34,963
There's a moment every team hits: the data scientist's model works beautifully in a notebook, and now someone has to make it answer 500 requests a second without falling over.

6
00:00:34,963 --> 00:00:41,550
That someone is a backend engineer, and the skills involved are 80% backend engineering and 20% ML.

7
00:00:41,550 --> 00:00:52,487
In 2026 this is one of the highest-paid intersections in the field — production ML integration commands a real salary premium precisely because the talent is scarce.

8
00:00:52,487 --> 00:00:59,963
This is the backend engineer's guide to serving a model: the concerns that don't exist in a notebook and the patterns that handle them.

9
00:00:59,963 --> 00:01:07,235
It leans on the same fundamentals as the rest of my backend writing — caching, rate limiting, and async APIs.

10
00:01:07,235 --> 00:01:11,021
Now, let's talk about A model is just a very expensive function.

11
00:01:11,021 --> 00:01:19,326
Strip away the mystique and an inference endpoint is a function call that happens to be slow, memory-hungry, and often GPU-bound.

12
00:01:19,326 --> 00:01:29,915
That reframing is useful, because it tells you the problems are the ones you already know — latency, throughput, concurrency, caching, failure handling — just with sharper constraints.

13
00:01:29,915 --> 00:01:34,879
Everything interesting is in making that middle line survive production traffic.

14
00:01:34,879 --> 00:01:38,737
Moving on to Latency vs throughput: pick your master.

15
00:01:38,737 --> 00:01:41,730
The first decision shapes everything else.

16
00:01:41,730 --> 00:01:54,555
Are you optimizing for latency (one user waiting on one prediction — fraud check, autocomplete) or throughput (maximizing predictions per second — batch scoring, recommendations)?

17
00:01:54,555 --> 00:01:56,358
They pull in opposite directions:

18
00:01:56,358 --> 00:02:04,411
Latency-first: process each request immediately, keep the model warm, accept lower GPU utilization..

19
00:02:04,411 --> 00:02:14,254
Throughput-first: batch requests together, because GPUs are dramatically more efficient processing 32 inputs at once than 32 inputs one at a time..

20
00:02:14,254 --> 00:02:17,175
Dynamic batching: the highest-leverage trick.

21
00:02:17,175 --> 00:02:28,125
The single biggest throughput win is dynamic batching — hold incoming requests for a few milliseconds, group them, run one batched inference, then fan the results back out.

22
00:02:28,125 --> 00:02:36,646
You trade a tiny, bounded latency increase for a multiple-X throughput gain because the GPU stops sitting idle between single requests.

23
00:02:36,646 --> 00:02:45,192
This is conceptually the same move as request coalescing in a cache stampede: collapse many concurrent calls into one expensive operation.

24
00:02:45,192 --> 00:02:50,180
Most serving frameworks give you dynamic batching as a config knob — use it.

25
00:02:50,180 --> 00:02:55,588
Next up: Concurrency: the GPU is a single, precious resource.

26
00:02:55,588 --> 00:03:00,216
In a normal web service you scale by adding threads/workers.

27
00:03:00,216 --> 00:03:05,949
With a GPU model, the GPU is the bottleneck and it doesn't parallelize like CPU.

28
00:03:05,949 --> 00:03:15,612
Fire 50 concurrent requests at one model instance and you don't get 50× — you get contention, memory pressure, and possibly an out-of-memory crash.

29
00:03:15,612 --> 00:03:20,685
The pattern: put a concurrency limit / queue in front of the GPU.

30
00:03:20,685 --> 00:03:25,709
Accept requests, queue them, and feed the model at the rate it can actually sustain.

31
00:03:25,709 --> 00:03:33,774
Past a threshold, shed load with a 429 (the rate-limiting patterns apply directly) rather than letting everything degrade.

32
00:03:33,774 --> 00:03:38,497
A bounded queue with backpressure beats an unbounded one that OOMs.

33
00:03:38,497 --> 00:03:42,776
Let's explore Cache aggressively — many inputs repeat.

34
00:03:42,776 --> 00:03:46,442
Inference is expensive; identical inputs are common.

35
00:03:46,442 --> 00:03:54,867
Cache predictions keyed by a hash of the (normalized) input, with a TTL appropriate to how often the model or data changes.

36
00:03:54,867 --> 00:04:03,581
For a recommendation or classification endpoint, a cache hit turns a 200ms GPU call into a 2ms Redis lookup.

37
00:04:03,581 --> 00:04:10,949
The Redis caching strategies — including jittered TTLs to avoid synchronized expiry — apply unchanged.

38
00:04:10,949 --> 00:04:17,139
Just be careful to include the model version in the cache key, so a model update doesn't serve stale predictions.

39
00:04:17,139 --> 00:04:20,168
Now let's look at Autoscaling and the cold-start tax.

40
00:04:20,186 --> 00:04:23,297
Model servers don't scale like stateless web pods.

41
00:04:23,297 --> 00:04:29,967
A new replica must load the model into GPU memory — often several seconds to tens of seconds.

42
00:04:29,967 --> 00:04:32,203
That cold start has consequences:

43
00:04:32,203 --> 00:04:33,681
Scale on the right signal.

44
00:04:33,681 --> 00:04:38,573
Queue depth or GPU utilization predicts saturation better than CPU..

45
00:04:38,573 --> 00:04:39,859
Keep a warm floor.

46
00:04:39,859 --> 00:04:45,268
Don't scale to zero if latency matters; the cold start will hit a real user..

47
00:04:45,268 --> 00:04:46,734
Scale ahead of demand.

48
00:04:46,734 --> 00:04:53,994
Because spin-up is slow, react early — reactive scaling arrives after the spike has already caused timeouts..

49
00:04:53,994 --> 00:04:57,828
Now, let's talk about Long or huge jobs: go async.

50
00:04:57,828 --> 00:05:04,054
Some inference is genuinely slow — large generative models, video, big batch scoring.

51
00:05:04,054 --> 00:05:06,506
Don't hold an HTTP connection for it.

52
00:05:06,506 --> 00:05:16,253
Use the async job pattern: accept the request, return 202 with a job ID, process on a worker, let the client poll or get a webhook.

53
00:05:16,253 --> 00:05:25,111
This is exactly the design in async, long-running APIs for AI agents, and it's how you keep a slow model from exhausting your web tier.

54
00:05:25,111 --> 00:05:28,501
Moving on to Failure modes a notebook never shows you.

55
00:05:28,501 --> 00:05:32,251
Production surfaces problems that don't exist offline.

56
00:05:32,251 --> 00:05:33,261
Budget for them:

57
00:05:33,261 --> 00:05:38,861
GPU OOM under concurrency — fix with the queue/concurrency limit above..

58
00:05:38,861 --> 00:05:46,482
Model/version skew — preprocessing in serving must exactly match training, or predictions silently degrade.

59
00:05:46,482 --> 00:05:47,876
Pin and test it..

60
00:05:47,876 --> 00:05:56,133
Input drift — real inputs diverge from training data over time; monitor input distributions, not just latency..

61
00:05:56,133 --> 00:06:01,301
Silent quality decay — the endpoint returns 200s with worse answers.

62
00:06:01,301 --> 00:06:06,602
Log predictions and sample them; latency dashboards won't catch this..

63
00:06:06,602 --> 00:06:16,746
Instrument it like any service — the Prometheus/Grafana/Jaeger stack — plus model-specific signals (prediction distribution, confidence, cache hit rate).

64
00:06:16,746 --> 00:06:18,465
Next up: The takeaway.

65
00:06:18,465 --> 00:06:23,705
Serving an ML model in production is a backend discipline wearing an ML hat.

66
00:06:23,705 --> 00:06:37,167
The model is an expensive function; your job is to make it fast (batching, warm instances), safe under load (concurrency limits, backpressure, caching), and observable (drift and quality, not just latency).

67
00:06:37,167 --> 00:06:48,405
Master that and you sit at one of 2026's scarcest, best-paid intersections — which, for Indian engineers especially, is exactly the skill that moves you up a salary band.

